Finally, we also run  a case (run5) where we adopt the 35 M$_\odot$ model, but increase the depletion factor from 0.0082 to 0.49, i.e. assuming the same depletion factor as for the power-law case, to disentangle the effect of the dust mass, composition, and distribution on the dynamics.

The dust physics is employed in {\textsc{krome} } via look-up tables obtained by the procedure discussed in \citet{Grassi2016}, which are only functions of the total density $n_\mathrm{tot}$ and the gas temperature $T$. We assume 20 bins in size per each grain type, which ensure a very good convergence on the results\footnote{Note that an acceptable convergence is already reached for 10 bins.}. The cooling and the H$_2$ formation on dust are in fact strongly affected by the number of bins, and assuming for instance one average size bin can lead to errors (see \citealt{Grassi2016}).  The total dust cooling  is defined as

