\noindent The gas opacity ($\tau_g$) is taken from \citet{Mayer2005}, while the optical constants for every individual dust species ($\tau_d$) are obtained from the refractive indexes reported by the Jena Database\footnote{\url{astro.uni-jena.de/Laboratory/OCDB}}. For the carbonaceous and silicates employed in the power-law distribution, the optical constants are from Bruce Draine's website\footnote{\url{astro.princeton.edu/~draine/dust/dust.diel.html}}.  The bulk densities are adopted from \citet{Nozawa2006}.

These tables do not introduce any approximation other than the discretization into bins, and provide very high efficiency when employed in 3D calculations. In addition, the tables could include an arbitrary number of bins and dust types without additional computational time, and then provide a very powerful method to realistically model the formation of extremely metal-poor stars or in general dust-enhanced media.  

