\section{Simulation setup}
We follow the collapse of two minihalos of 10$^6$~M$_\odot$ and 7$\times$10$^5$ M$_\odot$ starting from cosmological initial conditions as reported in \citet{Bovino2014}, by employing the hydrodynamical code \textsc{enzo} \citep{ENZO2014}. 
We select the most massive minihalo in a box of 300 kpc h$^{-1}$ and re-run our simulation with the box centered onto the selected minihalo adding two additional nested grids for an effective resolution of 512$^3$. 
From $z=99$ to $z=22$ we evolve the halos to reach a central temperature of $\sim$10$^3$~K at a density of 10$^{-23}$~g~cm$^{-3}$ and then enable the dust machinery. Radiative and mechanical feedback from the previous generation of stars is neglected here. We allow 29 levels of refinement, which yield a resolution at a sub-AU level in comoving units, and resolve the Jeans length by 64 cells.
Our refinement strategy is based on over-density, Jeans length and particle mass and is applied during the simulations to ensure that all physical processes are well resolved and the Truelove criterion \citep{Truelove1997,Federrath11} is fulfilled. 
A summary of our runs is reported in Table \ref{tab:runs}. 

