\section{Results}
In Fig. \ref{fig:figure2} we report the averaged thermal evolution for the ten runs performed for the two halos. In both cases the general trend is very similar, and clearly shows the effect of dust on the thermodynamics. Depending on the employed grain size distribution, we see a weaker or stronger cooling: the runs with low mass dust yield (run3, and run4) start to cool at densities above 10$^{-12}$ g cm$^{-3}$ and reach a minimum temperature of 600~K and 800~K for Halo 1, and 500 K and 700 K for Halo~2. This is in agreement with previous one-zone studies (e.g. \citealt{Schneider2012}). When we increase the amount of dust the cooling is much stronger and the effect is already visible at densities of 10$^{-18}$~g~cm$^{-3}$. The minimum temperature reached both in run2 and run5 is around 200~K and could lead to the formation of clumps with mass \mbox{$<$ 0.1 M$_\odot$}. The same dust content ($f_\mathrm{dep}$ = 0.49) provides similar results regardless of the choice of the distribution. In fact, assuming a power-law distribution or a more accurate distribution coming from a SN model (run2 with a progenitor of 35 M$_\odot$) produces differences of the order of \mbox{$\sim$50-100~K}. 

To better understand how these differences are reflected in the dynamical evolution, we show in Fig.~\ref{fig:figure3} the density projections along the x-axis for the different runs and the two considered halos, taken at a peak density of 3$\times$10$^{-10}$ g cm$^{-3}$. The density structure appears very similar in the two halos: when considering the cases with $f_\mathrm{dep}$ below (run2) or close (run4) to the threshold proposed by \citet{Schneider2012}, the collapse proceeds almost monolithically with a turbulent bulky structure which is similar to the primordial case (run1). This slightly depends on the selected halo:  for example for run4, Halo 2 shows a more compact structure compared to Halo 1 which seems more turbulent. When we analyse the cases with a high depletion factor, i.e. $f_\mathrm{dep} = 0.49$, the gas evolves in a more fragmented  and filamentary structure, reflecting the stronger cooling. 

