\caption{Dust grain distributions employed in this work. Left panel: SN distributions with $f_\mathrm{dep} = 0.0082$ for different dust species, and the standard power-law distributions for C and Si. Right panel: the same SN distributions where $f_\mathrm{dep}$ has been increased to match the dust mass typical of the power-law distribution, i.e. $f_\mathrm{dep} = 0.49$. Note that the y-scales are different.}\label{fig:figure1}
\end{figure*}
\end{center}

We report in Fig. \ref{fig:figure1} the grain size distributions employed in this work to better understand how these affect the density structure and the thermal evolution. On the left panel we clearly see that the power-law case has a higher mass content ($f_\mathrm{dep} = 0.49$ compared to the distribution obtained from SN model) and spans a smaller size-range. The distribution produced by SN models flattens at smaller radii as an effect of the reverse shock and extends down to very small sizes, of the order of 10$^{-8}$ cm. From simple considerations we know that the dust cooling goes as the inverse of the grain size, $\Lambda_\mathrm{dust} \propto a^{-1}$, and this means that smaller grains provide more cooling. 
Despite this, the comparison between run2 and run4 suggests that the amount of dust has a larger impact on the thermal evolution than its size distribution (Fig.~\ref{fig:figure2}).

Moreover, the standard galactic power-law distribution employed in run2 has a remarkable effect on the density structure compared to the SN model distribution which extends to smaller radii but has very low dust content.




This can be better disentangled when we look at the case with an increased dust mass for the SN model distribution (run5), right panel of Fig. \ref{fig:figure1}. By increasing the dust content $f_\mathrm{dep}$ from 0.0082 to 0.49 we are able to understand the real effect of the composition/distribution on the thermal evolution and density structure. When comparing the two cases with the same dust content but different distribution and composition (run2 and run5), i.e. different optical properties and size ranges (Fig. \ref{fig:figure1}), we obtain very similar results (see thermal evolution in Fig. \ref{fig:figure2}) and, in particular, similar filamentary density structures (Fig. \ref{fig:figure3}). This crucial result suggests that the grain composition and the shape of the size distribution \textit{do not strongly impact on the evolution of the collapsing halo and its density structure, as much as the mass yield does}. The latter turns out to be the key physical quantity to understand how the primitive star SDSS J102915+172927 was formed. 

\section{Conclusions and final remarks}
In this Letter we present 3D hydrodynamical calculations of two collapsing minihalos enriched by dust, starting from cosmological initial conditions. We employ the chemistry package {\textsc{krome} } \citep{Grassi2014} coupled with the hydrodynamical code \textsc{enzo} including (to our knowledge) the most accurate and detailed grain size distributions and dust physics in this kind of simulations. Two different types of grain distributions have been included: i) a standard power-law with composition and dust content similar to our galaxy, i.e. a mix of carbonaceous and silicates, and ii) a more realistic distribution for high-redshift environments. The latter comes from a SN core-collapse model which properly includes all the processes needed to follow the formation and the evolution of different types of grain \citep{Schneider2012}. This consists of a sum of log-normal distributions modified by the presence of reverse shocks which flattens the distribution at smaller radii. The two cases allow us to explore different dust compositions and distributions, and assess the effect of the dust physics on the dynamics of the collapsing minihalos. In addition, we explore one case where the outcome of the SN models has been modified by increasing the dust mass yield, and compare this with the results obtained by employing the standard power-law distribution. We found that the dust mass yield, expressed in terms of the depletion factor $f_\mathrm{dep}$, is the key quantity which has a strong impact on the dynamical and thermal evolution of the minihalos.

In fact, when we impose the same dust mass (i.e. $f_\mathrm{dep} = 0.49$) for the standard power-law distribution and the one coming from SN models, these show similar results and dynamical properties.

The composition and the size-range are not producing any remarkable difference, as similarly reported by the one-zone models by \citet{Ji2014}.
In addition, our results suggest that a threshold in dust mass exists, as proposed by \citet{Schneider2012}, but we also found that this is affected by the dynamical evolution of the individual halos and requires additional investigation via 3D hydrodynamical simulations. 

A quantitative and detailed comparison with previous 3D calculations \citep{Dopcke2011,Dopcke2013,Smith2015} is difficult to pursue as they employed different dust models and different initial setups.  \citet{Dopcke2013} reported temperatures between 200-500 K for metallicities of \mbox{10$^{-4}$~-~10$^{-5}$ $Z_\odot$}, in line with our results for the power-law distribution, but assuming an average grain size and different optical properties. In \citet{Smith2015} the final temperature reached is slightly higher but the density structure shows similar features as the findings discussed in this work. We further note, that using the realistic depletion factor from the SN models makes a strong difference for the thermodynamics and the dynamical behaviour. We found that the low amount of dust in run3 and run4 is below the threshold for which dust cooling becomes relevant.

The formation of dust in SN ejecta included here comes from classical nucleation theory, but other models as the chemical kinetic approach \citep{Cherchneff2009,Biscaro2014} may lead to different results. The differences between the two approaches have been discussed in \citet{Marassi2015}. The grain growth process can furthermore affect the dust mass yield threshold. As discussed by \citet{Chiaki2014}, even a low dust mass yield could produce an effective dust cooling as grains can grow by sticking from the gas phase during the collapse. Recently, a potential mechanism has been proposed to allow the formation of low-mass stars even for dust abundances below the global fragmentation threshold. \citet{Hopkins2015} introduced the so called ``promoted star formation" mechanism, which can be activated even in minihalos where the total metallicity is low, but a locally high dust mass could exist due to fluctuations induced by the dust dynamics. This model assumes that the dust distribution and composition in the early Universe is the same as the one observed for our galaxy. 

Finally, \citet{Peters2012} explored the effect of varying the adiabatic index ($\Gamma$) on the thermodynamics of a collapsing halo by employing an effective equation of state and including magnetic fields. They observed filamentary structure when $\Gamma < 1$, i.e. in the presence of strong cooling, which agrees with the results reported here. 

To conclude, the results presented in this work provide a relevant step forward to understand the main dust uncertainties and the parameters influencing the dynamical evolution of low-metallicity collapsing halos. 


